73&ndash;88.</li>

<li>Lillehammer, H., 2009. &ldquo;Reproduction, Partiality, and the
Non-Identity Problem,&rdquo; in M. Roberts and D. Wasserman (eds.),
pp. 231&ndash;248.</li>

<li>McMahan, J., 1981. &ldquo;Problems of Population Choice,&rdquo;
<em>Ethics</em>, 92(1): 96&ndash;127.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2006. &ldquo;Paradoxes of Abortion and
Prenatal Injury,&rdquo; <em>Ethics</em>, 116: 625&ndash;55.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2009. &ldquo;Asymmetries in the Morality of
Causing People to Exist,&rdquo; in M. Roberts and D. Wasserman (eds.)
2009, pp. 49&ndash;68.</li>

<li>Meacham, C., 2012. &ldquo;Person-Affecting View and Saturating
Counterpart Relations,&rdquo; <em>Philosophical Studies</em>, 158:
257&ndash;287.</li>

<li>Meyer, K., 2018. &ldquo;The Claims of Future Persons,&rdquo;
<em>Erkenntnis</em>, 83: 43&ndash;59. </li>

<li>Meyer, L., 2004. &ldquo;Historical Injustice and the Right of
Return,&rdquo; <em>Theoretical Inquiries in Law</em>, 5(2):
305&ndash;316.</li>

<li>Meyer, L and D. Roser, 2009. &ldquo;Enough for the Future,&rdquo;
in A. Gosseries and L. Meyer (eds.), pp. 219&ndash;248. </li>

<li>Mulgan, T., 2006. <em>Future People: A Moderate Consequentialist
Account of Our Obligations to Future Generations</em>, Oxford: Oxford
University Press.</li>

<li>Narveson, J., 1976. &ldquo;Moral Problems of Population,&rdquo; in
Bayles (ed.), pp. 59&ndash;80.</li>

<li>Noggle, R. 2019. &ldquo;Impossible Obligations and the
Non-Identity Problem,&rdquo; <em>Philosophical Studies</em>, 176:
2371&ndash;2390.</li>

<li>Parfit, D., 1976. &ldquo;On Doing the Best for Our
Children,&rdquo; in Bayles (ed.), pp. 100&ndash;115.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1982. &ldquo;Future Generations: Further
Problems,&rdquo; <em>Philosophy and Public Affairs</em>, 11:
113&ndash;72.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1986. &ldquo;Comments,&rdquo;
<em>Ethics</em>, 96: 854&ndash;62.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1987 (orig. 1984). <em>Reasons and
Persons</em>, Oxford: Clarendon Press.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2011. <em>On What Matters</em> (volumes 1
and 2), Oxford: Clarendon Press.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2017. &ldquo;Future People, the
Non-Identity Problem, and Person-Affecting Principles,&rdquo;
<em>Philosophy and Public Affairs</em>, 45(2): 118&ndash;157. </li>

<li>Parsons, J., 2003. &ldquo;Why the Handicapped Child Case Is
Hard,&rdquo; <em>Philosophical Studies</em>, 112: 147&ndash;162.</li>

<li>Persson, I., 2009. &ldquo;Rights and the Asymmetry Between
Creating Good and Bad Lives,&rdquo; in M. Roberts and D. Wasserman
(eds.) 2009, pp. 29&ndash;47.</li>

<li>Peters, P., 2004. <em>How Safe Is Safe Enough? Obligations to the
Children of Reproductive Technology</em>, New York: Oxford University
Press.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2009. &ldquo;Implications of the
Nonidentity Problem for State Regulation of Reproductive
Liberty,&rdquo; in M. Roberts and D. Wasserman (eds.) 2009, pp.
317&ndash;331.</li>

<li>Rachels, S., 1998. &ldquo;Is It Good to Make Happy People,&rdquo;
<em>Bioethics</em>, 12(2): 93&ndash;110.</li>

<li>R&auml;s&auml;nen, J., 2023. &ldquo;Defending the De Dicto
Approach to the Non-Identity Problem,&rdquo; <em>Monash Bioethics
Review</em>, 41: 124&ndash;135.</li>

<li>Reiman, J., 2007. &ldquo;Being Fair to Future People: The
Non-Identity Problem in the Original Position,&rdquo; <em>Philosophy
&amp; Public Affairs</em>, 35(1): 71&ndash;92.</li>

<li>Risberg, O. 2023. &ldquo;The Morality of Creating Lives Not Worth
Living: On Boonin&rsquo;s Solution to the Nonidentity Problem,&rdquo;
<em>Utilitas</em>, 35: 88&ndash;97.</li>

<li>Rivera-Lopez, E., 2009. &ldquo;Individual Procreative
Responsibility and the Non-Identity Problem,&rdquo; <em>Pacific
Philosophical Quarterly</em>, 90: 99&ndash;118.</li>

<li>Roberts, M., 1998. <em>Child Versus Childmaker: Future Persons and
Present Duties in Ethics and the Law</em>, Lanham, MD: Rowman &amp;
Littlefield.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2002. &ldquo;A New Way of Doing the Best
That We Can: Person-Based Consequentialism and the Equality
Problem,&rdquo; <em>Ethics</em>, 112(2): 315&ndash;50.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2007. &ldquo;The Nonidentity Fallacy: Harm,
Probability and Another Look at Parfit&rsquo;s Depletion
Example,&rdquo; <em>Utilitas</em>, 9: 267&ndash;311.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2008. &ldquo;What is the Wrong of Wrongful
Disability? From Chance to Choice to Harm to Persons,&rdquo; <em>Law
and Philosophy</em>, 28(1): 1&ndash;57.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2009. &ldquo;The Nonidentity Problem and
the Two Envelope Problem: When Is One Act Better for a Person than
Another?&rdquo; in M. Roberts and D. Wasserman (eds.) 2009, pp.
201&ndash;228.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2010. <em>Abortion and the Moral
Significance of Merely Possible People: Finding Middle Ground in Hard
Cases</em>, Dordrecht: Springer.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2011a. &ldquo;The Asymmetry: A
Solution,&rdquo; <em>Theoria</em>, 77: 333&ndash;367.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2011b. &ldquo;An Asymmetry in the Ethics of
Procreation,&rdquo; <em>Philosophy Compass</em>, 6(11): 765&ndash;776.
</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2022a. &ldquo;Nonidentity, Better Chance
and the Value of Existence: A Defense of Person Based
Consequentialism,&rdquo; in <em>The Oxford Handbook of Population
Ethics</em>, G. Arrhenius, K. Bykvist, T. Campbell and E.
Finneran-Burns (eds.), Oxford University Press, pp.
226&ndash;250.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2022b. &ldquo;The Value and Probabilities
of Existence,&rdquo; in <em>Ethics and Existence</em>, J. McMahan, T.
Campbell, J. Goodrich and K. Ramakrishnan (eds.), Philadelphia: Temple
University Press, pp. 38&ndash;60.</li>

<li>Roberts, M. and D. Wasserman (eds.), 2009. <em>Harming Future
Persons: Ethics, Genetics and the Nonidentity Problem</em>, Dordrecht:
Springer.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash; and D. Wasserman, 2017. &ldquo;Dividing and
Conquering the Nonidentity Problem,&rdquo; in M. Liao and C.
O&lsquo;Neil (eds.), pp. 81&ndash;98. </li>

<li>Robertson, J. A., 1994. <em>Children of Choice: Freedom and the
New Reproductive Technologies</em>, Princeton: Princeton University
Press.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2004. &ldquo;Procreative Liberty and Harm
to Offspring in Assisted Reproduction,&rdquo; <em>American Journal of
Law and Medicine</em>, 30: 7&ndash;40.</li>

<li>Savulescu, J. 2001. &ldquo;Procreative Beneficence: Why We Should
Select the Best Children,&rdquo; <em>Bioethics</em>, 15(5/6):
&ndash;413.</li>

<li>Scanlon, T., 2000. <em>What We Owe to Each Other</em>, revised
edition, Cambridge, MA: Harvard University Press. </li>

<li>Schwartz, T., 1978. &ldquo;Obligations to Posterity,&rdquo; in
<em>Obligations to Future Generations</em>, R. Sikora and B. Barry
(eds.), Philadelphia: Temple University Press, pp. 3&ndash;13.</li>

<li>Sher, G., 2005. &ldquo;Transgenerational Compensation,&rdquo;
<em>Philosophy &amp; Public Affairs</em>, 33: 181&ndash;200.</li>

<li>Shiffrin, S., 1999. &ldquo;Wrongful Life, Procreative
Responsibility, and the Significance of Harm,&rdquo; <em>Legal
Theory</em>, 5: 117&ndash;48.</li>

<li>Sikora, R. and B. Barry (eds.), 1978. <em>Obligations to Future
Generations</em>, Philadelphia: Temple University Press.</li>

<li>Singer, P., 2011. <em>Practical Ethics</em>, 3<sup>rd</sup> ed.
Cambridge University Press.</li>

<li>Smilansky, S., 2013. &ldquo;Morally, Should We Prefer Never to
Have Existed?&rdquo; <em>Australasian Journal of Philosophy</em>,
91(4): 655&ndash;666.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2017. &ldquo;The Nonidentity Problem:
United and Unconquered,&rdquo; in <em>Current Controversies in
Bioethics</em>, Matthew Liao and Collin O&rsquo;Neil (eds.), London:
Routledge, pp. 99&ndash;111.</li>

<li>Smolkin, D., 1999. &ldquo;Toward a Rights-Based Solution to the
Non-Identity Problem,&rdquo; <em>Journal of Social Philosophy</em>,
30: 195&ndash;96.</li>

<li>Steinbock, B., 2009. &ldquo;Wrongful Life and Procreative
Decisions,&rdquo; in M. Roberts and D. Wasserman (eds.) 2009, pp.
155&ndash;178.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, and R. McClamrock, 1994. &ldquo;When Is
Birth Unfair to the Child?&rdquo; <em>Hastings Center Report</em>, 24:
15&ndash;21.</li>

<li>T&auml;nnsj&ouml;, T., 2002. &ldquo;Why We Ought to Accept the
Repugnant Conclusion,&rdquo; <em>Utilitas</em>, 14(3):
339&ndash;359.</li>

<li>Temkin, L., 2012. <em>Rethinking the Good: Moral Ideals and the
Nature of Practical Reasoning</em>, Oxford: Oxford University
Press.</li>

<li>Tooley, M., 1998. &ldquo;Value, Obligation and the Asymmetry
Question,&rdquo; <em>Bioethics</em>, 12(2): 111&ndash;124.</li>

<li>Velleman, J. David, 2008. &ldquo;Persons in Prospect,&rdquo;
<em>Philosophy &amp; Public Affairs</em>, 36: 221&ndash;288.</li>

<li>Wasserman, D., 2005. &ldquo;The Nonidentity Problem, Disability,
and the Role Morality of Prospective Parents,&rdquo; <em>Ethics</em>,
116: 132&ndash;52.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2008. &ldquo;Hare on De Dicto Betterness
and Prospective Parents,&rdquo; <em>Ethics</em>, 118(3):
529&ndash;33.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2009. &ldquo;Harms to Future People and
